There are a few Canadian sites in EDU, also.

The COM, EDU, GOV, etc domains were set up with the intention that they
would be worldwide.  The folks at the NIC running them have told me that
they don't mind organizations outside the USA joining them, and it's
their decision to make.

There is a .CAN domain getting ready to start up, and I've made a point
of telling the few UUCP domains in Canada that have signed up for COM or
EDU that CAN will be coming along.  Several of them have indicated that
they prefer to be in EDU or COM, and in a few cases they will register
in both.  (Part of the university wants to be in EDU, and part in CAN,
for example, so they handle the magic internally to ensure that the
dual identity won't mess up the rest of the world.)

I just had an inquiry from Switzerland about joining EDU, but this was
just a misunderstanding, I think.  It's much more likely that they will
set up a .CH domain; there is strong pressure in Europe (and indeed just
about everywhere except the USA and Canada) to use country top level
domains.

	Mark

